@page "/"

<PageTitle>Hello Blazor Pages</PageTitle>

<section class="hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Blazor WebAssembly on GitHub Pages</p>
    <h1>Hello from a template-friendly starter.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
        This project keeps the app intentionally small so you can verify GitHub Pages hosting first,
        then evolve it into a real site without unpicking sample-specific logic.
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
        <a class="button primary" href="status">Open the route test</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="https://github.com/dotnet/blazor-samples" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">See the Blazor samples repo</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="panel-grid">
    <article class="panel">
        <h2>Why this repo exists</h2>
        <p>
            It proves a standalone Blazor WebAssembly app can build, test, and deploy to GitHub Pages
            from a modern repository layout with <code>/src</code> and <code>/tests</code>.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
        <h2>What makes Pages work</h2>
        <p>
            The deployment workflow publishes the app, rewrites the base path for the repository name,
            adds a SPA fallback, and uploads the final static site artifact to GitHub Pages.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
        <h2>How to turn this into your template</h2>
        <p>
            Rename the solution and project, keep the deployment workflow, and replace this page with
            your real content when you are ready.
        </p>
    </article>
</section>
